{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538380"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:27:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:27:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16167"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16167"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.02,0.74,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8858"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90188"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8858"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16167"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74433"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3165"},{"type":"tags","id":"3180"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30817"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90188"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by police after being found wandering in traffic. His parent reports he has become increasingly withdrawn over the past six months, spending most of his time alone in his room. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears dishevelled but is cooperative. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. During the mental state examination, his speech is minimal and slow. When he does speak, his responses are delayed and brief. Several times during the interview, he stops mid-sentence and stares blankly. After 10-15 seconds of silence, he appears confused and when prompted, cannot remember what he was discussing. He eventually discloses that he feels his thoughts are being removed from his mind by radio waves.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s predominant speech pattern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Poverty of speech","Mutism","Thought blocking","Psychomotor retardation","Catatonic stupor"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a diagnostic challenge due to the overlap of several phenomena. The patient demonstrates features that could suggest multiple diagnoses, but careful analysis reveals \u003Cstrong\u003Ethought blocking\u003C/strong\u003E as the predominant speech pattern. The key distinguishing feature is the sudden interruption of speech mid-sentence, followed by confusion and inability to recall previous thoughts, occurring multiple times during the interview. The presence of thought withdrawal delusions adds context to these episodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoverty of speech\u003C/strong\u003E refers to decreased quantity of spontaneous speech with brief, unelaborated responses. While this patient does display reduced speech output, the defining feature is not simply brevity but rather the sudden interruptions with inability to recall previous thoughts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMutism\u003C/strong\u003E describes a complete absence of verbal output. This patient is able to speak, albeit with interruptions, making mutism an incorrect characterization.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychomotor retardation\u003C/strong\u003E involves a general slowing of thought, speech, and movement. While the patient shows some slowing, the characteristic pattern of sudden stopping with confusion and amnesia for previous thoughts is more consistent with thought blocking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatatonic stupor\u003C/strong\u003E involves profound psychomotor slowing or immobility with minimal or no responsiveness to external stimuli. This patient remains interactive and responsive between episodes, making catatonic stupor an incorrect diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of negative symptoms (social withdrawal) and positive symptoms (thought withdrawal delusions) adds complexity to the presentation. However, the specific pattern of speech interruption with confusion and inability to recall previous thoughts is pathognomonic of thought blocking, a formal thought disorder commonly seen in schizophrenia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thought blocking is characterized by sudden interruption of thought processes and speech, followed by silence and inability to recall previous thoughts.","Distinguishing between different types of formal thought disorder requires careful observation of speech patterns and their relationship to underlying thought processes.","The presence of negative symptoms can make assessment of formal thought disorder more challenging."],"references":["Benjamin JS, Kaplan SJ. Sadock Comprehensive Textbook of Psychiatry.","Elmarasi O, Abdelhady S, Mahgoub Y. Thought Blocking as a Manifestation of Catatonia: A Case Report. The Journal of Nervous and Mental Disease. 2024 Feb 1;212(2):120-1."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74433"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16167"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74433"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-12T18:36:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-12T18:36:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8858"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90188"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/225"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Schizophrenia","synonyms":[],"description":nul